            <h2 class="section-title">Document Checklist for Real Estate Company Setup</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                
<h3 style="margin-top:24px;">For Company Incorporation (SPICe+)</h3>
<ul class="custom-list">
  <li>PAN and Aadhaar of each director and shareholder (Indian nationals).</li>
  <li>Notarised and apostilled passport, address proof, and bank statement (foreign nationals).</li>
  <li>Latest utility bill (not older than 60 days) and NoC from owner for the Gurugram registered office.</li>
  <li>Rent agreement or sale deed for the registered office in Gurugram.</li>
  <li>Two passport-size photographs of each director.</li>
  <li>Class 3 DSC of each director and authorised representative.</li>
  <li>Real-estate-tailored MoA and AoA drafts.</li>
  <li>Director Identification Number (DIN) for proposed directors with no existing DIN.</li>
</ul>
<h3 style="margin-top:24px;">For HARERA Gurugram Project Registration (Form A)</h3>
<ul class="custom-list">
  <li>DTCP licence and zoning approval.</li>
  <li>Title certificate or ownership documents of the project land.</li>
  <li>Sanctioned layout plan, building plan, and service plan.</li>
  <li>Project brochure with carpet area, parking, common areas.</li>
  <li>Audited balance sheet and profit and loss of the past 3 financial years (if existing entity).</li>
  <li>Project cost estimate certified by a Chartered Accountant.</li>
  <li>Section 4(2)(l)(D) escrow declaration on stamp paper.</li>
  <li>Allotment letter draft and Builder-Buyer Agreement draft per HARERA model.</li>
  <li>Pollution NoC, fire NoC, airport NoC (where applicable), forest NoC (where applicable).</li>
  <li>Declaration on absence of pending litigation against the project land.</li>
  <li>Promoter past project disclosure (last 5 years across India).</li>
</ul>
<h3 style="margin-top:24px;">For Statutory NoCs and DTCP Licence</h3>
<ul class="custom-list">
  <li>Land use change documents (CLU) where applicable.</li>
  <li>EDC and IDC payment plan to HSVP and licensing authority.</li>
  <li>Environmental clearance under EIA Notification 2006 (for projects above prescribed threshold).</li>
  <li>HSVP zonal plan compliance certificate.</li>
  <li>Aerial map and contour survey.</li>
</ul>


            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        
<tr><td>Object clause too narrow for future leasing or REIT</td><td>A boilerplate "construction and sale" object clause blocks future leasing income and REIT structuring. Patron drafts the MoA with an expansive but well-organised main-object clause covering development, sale, leasing, JV, fund management, and REIT participation - approved at name-reservation stage so it does not need MoA amendment later (Form MGT-14 plus board and shareholder approval).</td></tr>
<tr><td>HARERA Form A rejected on incomplete DTCP linkage</td><td>HARERA Gurugram routinely rejects Form A when the DTCP licence and zoning copy mismatch the site plan. Patron sequences DTCP first, runs a pre-submission match against HARERA technical checklist, and submits only when reconciliations are green - protects the Section 5(1) 30-day clock from resetting.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pricing on super area instead of carpet area</td><td>Post the HARERA Gurugram ruling of 27 April 2022, pricing on super area is treated as fraudulent. Patron rewrites the cost sheet, the Builder-Buyer Agreement, and the brochure to carpet-area-only pricing before HARERA filing - aligned with Section 2(k) RERA definition.</td></tr>
<tr><td>70 percent escrow leakage on project funds</td><td>Section 4(2)(l)(D) RERA mandates 70 percent of buyer collections to an escrow account dedicated to that project. Patron designs the chart of accounts, automates the bank sweep, and obtains the quarterly CA certification HARERA expects - any leakage attracts HARERA enforcement and Section 18 refund liability.</td></tr>
<tr><td>HARERA Gurugram vs Panchkula jurisdiction confusion</td><td>HARERA Gurugram covers entire Gurugram district under Notification 1/92/2017-1TCP dated 14 December 2017; HARERA Panchkula covers rest of Haryana. Cross-jurisdiction filing rejected. Patron confirms project pin code falls within Gurugram district before filing.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Section 80-IBA vs Section 115BAA election trade-off</td><td>Section 80-IBA affordable-housing deduction and Section 115BAA 22 percent concessional rate cannot be combined - electing 115BAA forfeits 80-IBA. Patron models both paths against project IRR and recommends election only after both scenarios are quantified.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Section 11 advertising display non-compliance</td><td>Brochures, websites and ads without HARERA registration number attract Section 59(2) penalty. Patron sets the display compliance into the marketing brief and runs a pre-launch audit on all creative and digital assets.</td></tr>
<tr><td>FDI sector restrictions</td><td>FDI permitted under automatic route in construction-development sector with FEMA conditions; EXCLUDED for real estate business (defined narrowly as trading in TDRs and farmhouses). Patron scopes the activity against FEMA Sector 16 definition before structuring FDI inflows.</td></tr>


                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

