<section id="faq-section" class="content-section" style="background-color: #ffffff;">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <div class="faq-expanded">
                <aside class="faq-expanded__aside">
                    <h2 class="faq-expanded__title">FAQs: Real Estate Company Registration in India - Gurugram in Gurugram</h2>
                    <p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Real Estate Company Registration in India - Gurugram for Gurugram businesses, answered by our CA and CS team.</p>
                    @include('partials.faq-enquiry-form', ['enquiryLocation' => 'Gurugram', 'enquiryService' => 'Real Estate Company Registration in India - Gurugram in Gurugram'])
                </aside>
                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the threshold for mandatory RERA registration?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Under Section 3(2) of the Real Estate (Regulation and Development) Act 2016, RERA project registration is mandatory where the project land area exceeds 500 square metres OR more than 8 apartments are involved (all phases combined). Below the threshold, project registration is not required. Renovation or repair work without new marketing or sale is also exempt. Above the threshold, advertising, marketing or accepting any booking amount without prior RERA registration is a Section 3 violation triggering penalty up to 10% of the estimated project cost under Section 59.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the difference between RERA developer and agent registration?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>RERA project registration under Section 3 applies to promoters (builders, developers, plot developers, redevelopment promoters) and is project-specific. RERA agent registration under Section 9 applies to brokers, channel partners, consultants and intermediaries who facilitate the sale of a RERA-registered project. Project registration uses Form A (state-specific variants); agent registration uses Form REA-I. Agent registration is typically valid for 5 years, while project registration runs until project completion timeline.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the 70% escrow account requirement under RERA?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 4(2)(l)(D) of the RERA Act 2016 mandates that 70% of the amounts realised from allottees for a real estate project must be deposited in a separate bank account opened for that specific project. Withdrawals from this account are linked to construction progress and require a certificate from the engineer, architect and chartered accountant verifying that the withdrawal is in proportion to construction completed. The 30% balance is for land cost. The escrow protects buyer money from being diverted across projects.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Can a builder sell on super area or only carpet area under RERA?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 4(2)(c) of the RERA Act 2016 mandates that sale must be on carpet area basis only. Carpet area is the net usable floor area of an apartment, excluding the area covered by external walls, areas under service shafts, exclusive balcony or verandah and exclusive open terrace area, but including the area covered by internal partition walls. Super area and built-up area sale practices are no longer permitted. Builders who continue super-area pricing face Section 4 violation proceedings and Section 18 default claims from buyers.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What are the GST rates for under-construction property?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Under Notification 03/2019 - Central Tax (Rate), effective 1 April 2019, the new regime applies: 1% without ITC for affordable residential (carpet area up to 60 sqm in metros or 90 sqm non-metros AND price up to INR 45 lakh); 5% without ITC for non-affordable residential under-construction; 12% with ITC for commercial under-construction; exempt for completed units with Occupancy Certificate (treated as sale of immovable property). Sale of pure land without development is exempt under Schedule III of the CGST Act 2017.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Which real estate projects are exempt from RERA?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Under Section 3(2) of RERA 2016, the following are exempt from project registration: projects where land area does not exceed 500 square metres AND apartments do not exceed 8 (all phases combined); projects completed with Completion Certificate before RERA implementation date in the respective state; renovation or repair work that does not involve marketing, advertising, selling or new allotment. Government projects funded entirely by the central or state government may also be exempt subject to state-specific rules. Patron diagnoses RERA applicability at intake.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the interest payable under Section 18 RERA?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 18 of the RERA Act 2016 provides that if the promoter fails to complete or hand over possession of an apartment by the date specified in the agreement, the allottee can either withdraw with a refund of the amount paid plus interest, or continue the project and receive interest until possession is handed over. The interest rate is typically the State Bank of India highest Marginal Cost of Funds based Lending Rate (MCLR) plus 2% in most state rules. This is a significant contingent liability that builders need to provision for from the start of every project.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does RERA project registration take?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>State RERA Authority must dispose of a registration application within 30 days under Section 5 of the RERA Act 2016. If not responded to within 30 days, the project is deemed registered. In practice, including document reconciliation, query responses and the State RERA review, project registration takes 30 to 60 working days post-Form A submission. Agent registration under Section 9 is typically faster at 15 to 30 working days. For a Gurugram project, file via rera.delhi.gov.in; Patron handles the full process end-to-end.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

